
    Florida mid-terms: Democrat Andrew Gillum concedes to Ron DeSantis

        

    
        
                
                Image copyright
                 Reuters
                
            
            
            Image caption
                
                    Andrew Gillum admitted defeat following a recount in Florida.
                
            Democrat Andrew Gillum has admitted defeat to his Republican rival in the race to be named Florida's governor - for the second time.Mr Gillum, who hoped to be Florida's first black governor, congratulated Ron DeSantis in a tweet, 10 days after he first conceded the 6 November election.He withdrew the initial concession after Mr DeSantis's lead narrowed to 0.41%, triggering a recount.A recount has also been ordered in Florida's Senate race.US mid-terms: Why the elections still aren't overUnofficial results revealed Republican former governor Rick Scott was leading Democrat Bill Nelson by just 0.15%.
    
        
Florida is a well-known swing state and has a history of close elections, so the slim margins are not a major surprise.'Bring Florida together'Taking to Twitter on Saturday night, Mr Gillum - the mayor of state capital Tallahassee - paid tribute to his team, thanked voters and vowed to "keep fighting"."In the end, I believe that we will win," he wrote.
    
        
